## Common Shift Schedule Types

### 8-Hour, 7-Day Schedule (Shift Schedule #1)

**Coverage:** 24 hours/day, 7 days/week

**Advantages:**
- Built-in overtime and shift premiums increase compensation
- About 273 workdays per year (91 day, 91 evening, 91 night shifts)
- One weekend out of four is off (13 weekends/year)
- Each weekend off is four days long
- Weekend follows day-shift for better time-off advantage
- Overtime normally worked on scheduled workday, making time-off predictable

**Disadvantages:**
- Weekly rotation increases fatigue levels
- Working seven consecutive shifts is tiring
- Working 14 out of 15 days in weeks 2-4 is very tiring, especially with half on night shift

**Variations:**
- Lunches may be paid or unpaid
- Shifts may be fixed or oscillating (2 rotate, 1 fixed)
- Variable staffing requirements
- Night shifts may be first or last shift of day
- Shift-breaker can reduce scheduled overtime

### Semi-Continuous, 6-Day Shift Schedule

**Context:** Many people consider shift work 5-day or 7-day proposition. Once overtime on weekends becomes too high, companies often try to "leap" to continuous operations.

**Challenge:** Leap from 5 to 7 days is difficult for:
- Company (operational challenges)
- Workforce (lifestyle changes)

**Alternative:** Consider 6-day schedules as intermediate step

